2 Background
LoRA involves freezing a pretrained weight matrix Wpretrained‚ààRd√ók, and learning only a low-rank pertur-
bation to it, denoted here as ‚àÜ, as follows:
Wfinetuned =Wpretrained + ‚àÜ
‚àÜ =Œ≥rAB, A‚ààRd√ór, B‚ààRr√ók.
Most common implementations initialize A0‚àºN(0,1), B 0= 0and set the scalar Œ≥r=Œ±/rwith a controllable
hyperparameter Œ±. The user chooses which Wpretrained to adapt (‚Äútarget modules‚Äù), the rank r<<d,k , and
the hyperparameter Œ±. By doing so, only d√ór+r√ókparameters are trained per module instead of d√ók,
which reduces the memory and FLOPS required for computing the gradient. As an example, applying a
r= 16LoRA adapter to a 7B weight matrix with d=k= 4096trains<1%of the original parameter count.
Appendix Sec. H lays out the approximate memory savings by LoRA during training.
LoRA‚Äôs introduction and first applications targeted only the WqandWvmatrices in the self-attention
module (Hu et al., 2021). Since then, it has become best practice to target all transformer modules
(Raschka, 2023; Dettmers et al., 2024), i.e., {W(l)
